  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much does getting a patent cost?",
  "response": "The cost of obtaining a patent can vary significantly based on several factors, including the type of patent, complexity of the invention, geographic location, and whether you hire a patent attorney. Here\u2019s a general breakdown of potential costs:\n\n1. **Filing Fees**: \n   - **Provisional Patent Application**: Typically ranges from $75 to $300 for a small entity (individual or small business) and up to $1,500 for larger entities, depending on the filing method.\n   - **Non-Provisional Patent Application**: Filing fees can range from about $300 to over $1,700, again depending on entity size and the specific type of patent.\n\n2. **Patent Attorney Fees**: Hiring a patent attorney can be one of the most significant costs. Attorney fees can range from $5,000 to $15,000 or more, depending on the complexity of the invention and the amount of time required to prepare the application.\n\n3. **Search Fees**: Conducting a patent search to determine if your invention is novel can cost anywhere from $500 to $3,000.\n\n4. **Maintenance Fees**: After a patent is granted, maintenance fees are required to keep the patent in force. These fees can range from a few hundred dollars to several thousand dollars, depending on how long the patent is active.\n\n5. **Additional Costs**: There may be additional costs for drawings, translations (if filing internationally), and responses to office actions or appeals if required.\n\nOverall, the total cost of obtaining a patent can range from $5,000 to $20,000 or more. It's advisable to budget for these costs and consider consulting with a patent attorney to understand the specific expenses related to your invention.",
